We recommended and the management agreed that the:
Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count of property and equipment and prepare/submit the RPCPPE as of December 31, 2021;
Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer prepare the PPELCs and PCs, respectively, for each PPE account and update the records regularly;
Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer both reconcile their records and do it regularly or every quarter, if possible; and
One-time cleansing of PPE account balances without available record of accountability should be availed of pursuant to the guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006 to come up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to its existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the management agreed that the:
Municipal Accountant submit copy of the Mayor’s or Business Permit and list of beneficiaries signifying their receipt of good/supplies, or any proof of distribution to and receipt by the beneficiaries of goods such as photo documentation, as required under GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 and PD No. 1445, otherwise, submit justification on the non-submission of such documents;
BAC strictly comply with the mandatory posting of the updated APP, NOA and other relevant information in the GPPB online portal to promote accountability and transparency in the conduct of Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act;
Warranty provision should be included in the contract/Purchase Order to guarantee that the contractor shall perform all his responsibilities stipulated therein; and
Henceforth, Municipal Accountant be more vigilant in the processing of claims on 20% DF by requiring compliance in the submission of complete documentary requirements before effecting payment to establish validity and propriety of the transactions and to avoid suspension/disallowance in audit.

We recommended that management;
(i) minimize or stop the practice of serving meals and snacks for entertaining guests or visitors in the normal course of conducting official functions and during ordinary staff meetings or conferences in order to prevent the
 incurrence of irregular an unnecessary expenditures and wastage of government funds;

We recommended that:

The Municipal Accountant adjusts the previously recorded RPT and SET Receivable based on the Certified List of Delinquent Accounts, to correct the RPT and SET Receivables balance and deferred RPT/SET Income as of December 31, 2019;
The Municipal Assessor prioritize the yearly submission of the Assessment Roll (AR) to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
The Municipal Treasurer, based on AR, immediately update the RPTAR/TIC and then the Certified List of Taxpayers (CLT) showing real property taxes due and collectible for the year; and then submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as basis in the setting-up of RPT and SET Receivables for ensuing year.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant adjusts the previously recorded RPT and SET Receivable based on the Certified List of Delinquent Accounts, to correct the RPT and SET Receivables balance and deferred RPT/SET Income as of December 31, 2019;
The Municipal Assessor prioritize the yearly submission of the Assessment Roll (AR) to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
The Municipal Treasurer, based on AR, immediately update the RPTAR/TIC and then the Certified List of Taxpayers (CLT) showing real property taxes due and collectible for the year; and then submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as basis in the setting-up of RPT and SET Receivables for ensuing year.

We recommended that management strictly follow the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles prescribed under COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977, as amended by COA Circular No. 92-61A dated April 2, 1992
Require all drivers to prepare a Driver’s Trip Ticket with all information required properly supplied and a Monthly Report of Official Travels for each vehicle  by summarizing in chronological order of his trips for the month. Trip Tickets must be duly signed by the authorized passenger/s after each trip;
See to it that requisitioning officer must accomplished and duly approved RIV or equivalent (PR) as the basis of procuring gasoline and oil from a gasoline service station;
Prepare and submit a monthly fuel consumption report  showing among others, the different types of motor vehicles utilized by the agency during the month, total distance traveled, total fuel used and the normal fuel consumption for each vehicle, pursuant to COA Circulars 75-6 dated  November 7, 1975 and  77-61 dated September 26, 1977.
Investigate responsible officials that cause excessive procurement of gasoline based on Normal Travel, 4-5 km per liter as per COA Memo No. 76-23 and if unjustified shall be disallowed in audit.

We recommended that management;
(i) minimize or stop the practice of serving meals and snacks for entertaining guests or visitors in the normal course of conducting official functions and during ordinary staff meetings or conferences in order to prevent the
 incurrence of irregular an unnecessary expenditures and wastage of government funds;

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant adjust the previously recorded RPT and SET Receivable based on the Certified List of Delinquent Accounts, to correct the RPT and SET Receivables balance and deferred RPT/SET Income as of December 31, 2018;
The Municipal Assessor prioritize the yearly submission of the Assessment Roll (AR) to the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
The Municipal Treasurer, based on AR, immediately update the RPTAR/TIC and then the Certified List of Taxpayers (CLT) showing real property taxes due and collectible for the year; and then submit the same to the Municipal Accountant as basis in the setting-up of RPT and SET Receivables for ensuing year.

We recommended that BAC Secretariat:
Submit copy of infrastructure contracts to COA within five working days from perfection thereof for review and evaluation pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001;
Document and monitor the flow or movement of the contracts to establish accountability for the non-submission of contracts for audit.
